descript.abstract:
This file is a digital geospatial Environmental Systems Research Institute (Esri) ArcGIS polyline feature class of Street Midlines in Cook County, Illinois. The data are stored as a polyline feature class in an Esri ArcGIS Version 9.3 geodatabase.
The Street Midlines in this feature class are derived from an earlier project that collected all roadways in Cook County. During this earlier project, significant roadway features were stereocompiled from 1998 aerial photography to produce a dataset that was formerly referred to as "Cook County Board of Commissioners, Illinois 1:1200-Scale 1998 Street Midlines, Version 1.0, December 2007." In some cases, linear features in the street midline layer could not be compiled photogrammetrically as they were obscured by vegetation or shadows. In other circumstances, a linear feature may have run through an underground tunnel or underpass or otherwise was obscured from view on the aerial photography. For these cases, the linear path of the feature was interpreted and that segment was coded as such.
The Street Midlines in this feature class represent the interpreted midline between the compiled edges of pavement. Unimproved rights-of-way are also included in this database.
The Street Midlines have been maintained and updated planimetrically for new data or changes to existing features with the acquisition of successive County orthoimagery missions flown in 2003 and 2009.
This dataset is projected using the Transverse Mercator map projection. The grid coordinate system used is the Illinois State Plane Coordinate System, East Zone (Zone Number Zone 3776, FIPS 1201), NAD83/97 HARN (horizontal datum) with ground coordinates expressed in U.S. Survey Feet.
descript.purpose:
The purpose of the street midline feature class is to offer a comprehensive and accurate street database, at the enterprise level, to a wide variety of governmental jurisdictions, including, but not limited to, the Cook County Clerk's Office , the Assessor's Office, the Highway Department, Department of Public Health, Circuit Courts, the Revenue Department, Sheriff's Police, Animal Control and E911 services.
More specifically, this street midline feature class is intended to support more effective geocoding and routing business requirements. Some examples of the ways in which this feature class will support business processes and applications include:
- Elections Department: verification of registered voter locations, polling locations, redistricting; Assessor's Office: assessment, neighborhood analysis, inspections, and routing. - Revenue Department: compliance for statutory taxes and fees, and field inspections. - Sheriff's Police: incident management, and crime analysis. - Emergency Telephone System Board (E911): dispatch services, and address assignments in unincorporated Cook County.
descript.supplinf:
The metadata for this data set is one (1) of a series of two (2) reports. In addition to this metadata report, metadata exists for Address Points.
This dataset was also created to enhance an existing enterprise-wide GIS database that supports current and proposed applications involving executive decision and policy development, public access, land records management, planimetric mapping, infrastructure management, economic development, engineering, map production, and various land data analyses.

procstep.procdesc:
COOK COUNTY STREET MIDLINE ANALYSIS
A. Contributory Datasets
1. Street Midline Feature Class A pre-existing Esri polyline feature class that depicted the location of street midlines in Cook County served as the starting point for this project. This particular feature class was the product of an iniative, completed in 1998, to collect significant roadway features using 1998 aerial photography. Data for this feature class originally came from the US Census TIGER files. Since then, some improvements of the address range data have been made but the street midline feature class still lacked the pre-requisite completeness and accuracy to effectively support County functions such as dispatching.
B. Street Midline Attribute Analysis
Pro-West & Associates, Inc. (PWA) analyzed the street midlines to quantify the extent of the address range and spatial errors, and omissions in the current geodatabase. PWA performed the analysis using a customized address range analyzer software program. A Microsoft Access program was used to identify the following types of attribute errors:
> Geocoding overlaps > Unequal left/right ranges > Gaps in geocoding > Address ranges with zeros > Odd/even discrepancies > Duplicate line segments > Directionality issues > Street name mismatches between the street midline layer and the address point layer
Street midline types that were analyzed for errors included:
> Other Roads > Private Roads > Expressway Frontage > ISTHA Frontage > Standard Road Frontage > Toll Frontage > Midline Unimproved ROW > E911 > Private Unimproved
Street midline segments were flagged when any of its attributes satisfied an error condition. Each error was flagged according to error type, and later classified by PWA and then distributed via a web-based project tracking site for review by the County. PWA reviewed each error and, where necessary, made edits to the street midline feature class using reference documentation provided by the County.
Reference documentation, used by the County and PWA, to validate attributes included MSAG, Tele Atlas MultiNet Data, Delorme Street Atlas, Rand McNally Atlas, and existing GIS data held at the County.
C. Street Midline Spatial Analysis
Esri ArcGIS version 10 was used to assist in the identification of some spatial errors. Other spatial errors were identified through PWA technician analysis and spatial queries written against certain GIS datasets, such as municipal boundaries.
Street midlines were analyzed for the following spatial errors:
> Poor alignment with more accurate GIS data, e.g., aerial photos, parcels, etc. > Unnecessary or missing line segments. > Multiple splits along a street. > Split midlines based on political boundaries, e.g., municipality, township, etc.
Using ArcMap, the following topology rules were used to identify spatial errors:
> Street midline layer must not have dangles > Street midline layer must not self-intersect > Street midline layer must not self-overlap > Street midline layer must not overlap > Street midline layer must not intersect

procstep.procdesc:
STREET MIDLINE SCHEMA CREATION
A. Schema Creation
The Street Midline schema was developed by combining elements of the "Northeastern Illinois Counties GIS Managers Consortium Standard" (NEIL) with elements of the original street midline feature class that served as a major contributor to this project. The NEIL standard is a publication of the Northeastern Illinois Counties GIS Managers Consortium (Consortium), of which Cook County is a member, which was established to design and implement data sharing standards to facilitate transboundary business processes such as emergency management, crime analysis, and epidemiological events.
The following elements, contained in the original street midline feature class schema, were removed for the purposes of this project:
> ALIAS_NAME > "CHS_NO" > "DISTRICT" > "FIPSL" > "FIPSR" > "FLAG" > "FROM_ST" > "INTRP" > "LANES" > "PATROL" > "PLOW_ID" > "PLOWED" > "PREWET" > "ROAD_TYPE" > "SEC_NO" > "SEC_NUM" > "SECTION_ID" > "SEGMENT" > "SYS_NO" > "SYSTEM" > "TAXMAP_ID" > "TLID" > "TO_ST" > "TRANS_ID" > "VIS"
The following elements, contained in the original street midline feature class schema, were renamed for the purposes of this project:
> Element changed from: "EDIT_DATE" to: "EDITTIME" > Element changed from: "EDITOR_ID" to: "EDITOR" > Element changed from: "FRADDL" to: "LADDRFROM" > Element changed from: "FRADDR" to: "RADDRFROM" > Element changed from: "MUNIL" to: "LCITY" > Element changed from: "MUNIR" to: "RCITY" > Element changed from: "POST_NAME" to: "FULSTNAAB" > Element changed from: "REVIEW_ID" to: "REVIEWER_ID" > Element changed from: "ST_NAME" to: "STNAME" > Element changed from: "ST_PREFIX" to: "STNAMEPRD " > Element changed from: "ST_SUFFIX" to: "STNAMEPOD" > Element changed from: "ST_TYPE" to: "STNAMEPOT" > Element changed from: "TOADDL" to: "LADDRTO" > Element changed from: "TOADDR" to: "RADDRTO" > Element changed from: "UniqueID" to: "ORGUNIQUEID"
The following elements were created for the purposes of this project:
> "LONGITUDE" > "LATITUDE" > "UNIVRSLDT" > "COORDACCU" > "LUSPSST" > "RUSPSST" > "STNAMEPRM" > "STNAMEPRT" > "STNAMEPOM" > "FULLSTNA" > "STNAMEPRD1" > "STNAMEPRM1" > "STNAMEPRT1" > "STNAME1" > "STNAMEPOT1" > "STNAMEPOD1" > "STNAMEPOM1" > "FULLSTNA1" > "FULSTNAAB1" > "HONSTNAME" > "HONSTNAME1" > "HWYTYPE" > "HWYNO" > "FULLHINA" > "HWYTYPE1" > "HWYNO1" > "FULLHINA1" > "HWYTYPE2" > "HWYNO2" > "FULLHINA2" > "HWYTYPE3" > "HWYNO3" > "FULLHINA3" > "CFCCCODE" > "GNISMUNIL" > "GNISMUNIR" > "GNISTWP" > "GNISCNTY" > "GNISSTATE" > "ZIPL" > "ZIPR" > "EDITTYPE" > "OPSTATUS" > "SPDLIMIT" > "LENGTH" > "MINUTE" > "ONEWAY" > "HTRESTRC" > "MAJORROAD" > "PWA_COMMENT" > "GLOBALID" > "ANOMALY"
The Street Midline schema had been reviewed and modified by County officials during the course of this project. The final Street Midline schema was published September, 2011. Please refer to the Entity_and_Attribute_Detail_Citation section to view elements of the schema.
B. Data Loading
Data associated with the original street midline feature class was then extracted, transformed, and loaded into the new schema for the purposes of this project. With the exception of data stored in "ALIAS_NAME", values were loaded intact. Data stored in "ALIAS_NAME" was "mapped" to two elements: "HWYTYPE" and "HWYNO". In instances when the data in "ALIAS_NAME" included the character "/" (slash denoted the presence of an additional highway type and highway number value pair), then each value pair was "mapped" to one or more instance of "HWYTYPE" and "HWYNO". The data model supported up to four instances of "HWYTYPE" and "HWYNO".

procstep.procdesc:
STREET MIDLINE FEATURE CLASS CREATION
A. Splitting of Street Midline Segments
The existing Street Midline feature class contained many splits that had been deemed unnecessary since the data was originally developed. During this project, and in the future, a Street Midline feature would be split using the following criteria:
> 1. Intersection: > a. If a street midline feature intersected another street midline feature at the same grade, > then the features would be split. > 2. Municipality Boundary > a. A street midline feature would be split at a municipal boundary. > i. The Municipality feature class would be used to create these splits. > (Special exceptions to this rule exist if the Municipal boundary is found to be > following a right-of-way instead of the midline.) > 3. Township Boundary > 4. Bridges (grade separation) > a. If a street midline segment runs onto a bridge over another street midline that is at > a different grade (meaning it is above ground), then the street midline would be split > at the beginning and end of the bridge. > i. If the segment carries addressing attributes, then the bridge segment would > be given two addresses. (Example: 150-150 and 151-151 - The next segment will > start with 152 and 153.) > b. If a street midline segment runs onto a bridge that crosses water, then it is deemed to > be at grade and no split is required. > c. A street midline segment that runs under a bridge does not require a split (There is no > true intersection between the street midline segments.) > 5. Attribution > a. If a change in attribution occurs for any field in the StreetMidline feature class, > then a split is required. > b. If the only attribute difference is in the existing editor name/date fields, then the > segment will be merged. > i. The editor name /date that are the most current will remain on the segment.
B. Archiving Street Midline Segments
Any street midline segments that were dedicated and had not been improved were removed from Street Midline feature class and placed in a new feature class UnimprovedROWLine. Any questionable segments were left in the Street Midline feature class and flagged by a discrepancy point.
Roadways that were improved, either dedicated or private, were represented in the Street Midline feature class, regardless of whether the segments were or were not addressable. Any street midline segments that were once improved and had subsequently been removed were transferred from Street Midline feature class to the ArchivalStreetMidline feature class.
C. Street Midline - Subtypes
Subtypes that required address ranges were validated and corrected as needed. Street midline segments typed as Other Roads or Private Road were validated using the Right-Of-Way feature class, with the understanding that Other Roads resided within dedicated ROW while Private Road features did not.
Street midline segments that were not through streets and serviced a single use including, but not limited to, rail yards, mall parking lots, and quarries were moved to the subtype of Private Unaddressed.
Subtypes that had been marked as Review Type were assigned a subtype during the enhancement process by PWA. These road segments were originally marked with subtypes that were unconventional to the type standard (CountyQA, Post2003Dedication, Post2003PVT, USGSCapturedRoad, USGSCapturedPVT, and USGS2008). The original subtype code would remain in the Street Midline feature class in the field named ORGTYPECODE (Original Type Code) so that Cook County could update other associated feature classes.
D. City Code Verification
Spatial queries were used based on street midline location within the municipality to verify and populate the LCITY and RCITY attributes. PWA manually reviewed the street midlines on the edge of municipalities to ensure that the attributes for these segments were populated correctly. (Manual checks were warranted because not all municipal layer boundaries follow street midlines.) Municipal attribute fields for street midlines that border unincorporated township areas were populated with the township name (e.g., HANOVER TWP) not UNINC.
E. Street Name Authentication
Many different street midline name fields existed in the new schema and many had been populated through the loading procedures described in Process Step 2. This meant that some of the named features may have been incorrect or fields were incorrectly populated according to the new schema standard.
Full Street Name and Full Street Name Abbreviated were compared to make sure they were the same with the only difference being the abbreviation of the directional's and the street type. Since these fields had been populated, during the load, by different fields, they did not always correspond. In cases where the names did not correspond, additional source information was used to verify the correct street name. These sources included:
> MSAG > Municipal Sources > Parcel PIN table concatenation of STREET_DIRECTION and STREET_NAME and STREET_SUFFIX > Clerk Tax Maps (Right-of-way Annotation) > Street Name for AddressParcel (point) layer > Tele Atlas MultiNet Data > Delorme Street Atlas 2009 (data referenced from another application) > Rand McNally Atlas (hard copy book) > Google Maps (street name) > Google Street View (if sign can be read from street level photography)
A subset of these sources were used to verify each conflicting street midline segment's name. If the MSAG street name attribute matched one of the names existing in the Street Midline data, this was deemed its primary name (road types and directional's were standardized). Automated processes had been developed to run checks on the existing Full Street Name and the street name shown in the MSAG table. Discrepancies were flagged and further investigation occurred using additional sources to clarify the correct street midline name.
If signage was available for review, this was used for the primary street name 100% of the time. In most cases the additional name was attributed on the street midline segment in the Full Street Name 1 field (and associated fields).
A street midline name that used a numeral value was entered into the database as a figure including the ordinal suffix. Example 1st, 2nd, 3rd, 4th, etc.
The same sources, as shown above, were used to identify and attribute the addressable street midline segments that appeared as UNKNOWN. If an unknown segment could not be assigned a name and was clearly a road on the aerial photography; it was flagged in the Anomaly field with the statement "UNKNOWN MIDLINE NAME" and provided to the County for further review.
US highways, State Highways, and County Roads would always have the named road in the Full Street Name, while Highway type and number would be represented in the Highway Type and Highway Route Number fields. (Interstates would carry the Interstate with route number in the Full Street Name and Full Street Name Abbreviated fields - provided by ETSB).
If a street midline had two street names, the midline will retain whichever is deemed to be the primary street name and the other name would be inserted into the Street Name 1 attribute fields. The address points along that segment would be given the primary street name and not Street Name 1. In addition, comments would be added to the address points to show that the name was changed to match the primary street name.
Street Names were assigned as follows:
The MSAG and the information received from the communities would be the basis for enhancing the street midline names. Inconsistencies had been found when analyzing the MSAG and community information. These inconsistencies were managed in the following way when they arose.
> 1. If the MSAG contains a directional, then the directional WILL BE applied to the > street midline segments. > 2. If the MSAG does not contain a directional but a directional is needed due to the > city grid, then the directional WILL BE applied to the street midline segments. > a. The street midline segment will be given an MSAG Status of "UPDATE MSAG RECORD" > 3. If MSAG and community data DO NOT agree on the street name suffix (AVE, ST, TRL, CT, > LN, DR, etc), then the PIN table/Address Parcel point data will be referenced and > the most consistent value WILL BE used in naming the street midline segments. > a. Flags will be set in the appropriate tables identifying the information that > does not agree with what is currently in the Street Midline feature class. > This information will be delivered to Cook County upon project completion. > 4. If MSAG and Community data DO NOT agree on the street name spelling, then the > Community data and PIN table/Address Parcel point data will be referenced and the > most consistent value WILL BE used in naming the street midline segments. > a. Flags will be set in the appropriate tables identifying the information that > does not agree with what is currently in the Street Midline feature class. > This information will be delivered to Cook County upon project completion. > 5. Street midline segment names that DO NOT currently exist in the MSAG and have > structures addressed from them (according to Community data) are being flagged in > the StreetMidline feature class with the comment "SHOULD BE IN MSAG" > 6. Street midline segment names that DO NOT currently exist in the MSAG and DO NOT have > structures addressed from them (according to Community/PIN data) are being flagged > in the StreetMidline feature class with the comment "NOT IN MSAG" > 7. The communities of Robbins, Phoenix, Dixmoor, Ford Heights, Stone Park, North Lake, > and Golf MSAG are located in the Cook County MSAG.
F. Address Range Confirmation
Address range fields (LADDRFROM, LADDRTO, RADDRFROM, RADDRTO) were analyzed with a series of automated processes to check for:
> 1. Addressing overlaps > 2. Unequal left/right ranges > 3. Gaps in address ranges > 4. Address ranges with zeros > 5. Odd/even discrepancies
Divided highways were represented in the Street Midline feature class by one line for each set of lanes. Zero address ranges were applied to the median side of each segment. This geometry was created by Cook County and where the geometry did not follow the above statement, discrepancies were provided for further review.
Address range attributes were also verified against existing addresses along each street midline segment. This automated process determined if the existing address point fell along the correct segment. If addresses did not fall within the given range of the street midline segment, it was flagged.
PWA focused enhancement efforts on the returned conflicts. All flagged segments were reviewed and edited, or marked for further review. If marked for further review, insufficient information was available to make an educated decision and it may need to be reviewed further by the County.
G. Routing Information
The attributes for one way and speed limit were transferred from Tele Atlas data to the respective street midline segment.
H. Street Midline Attribution
Many of the NEIL Standard attributes could be populated for the entire County before the final delivery of the data. These included: LONGITUDE, LATITUDE, UNIVRSLDT, COORDACCU, LUSPSST, RUSPSST, CFCCCODE, GNISMUNIL, GNISMUNIR, GNISTWP, GNISCNTY, GNISSTATE, ZIPL, ZIPR, and MAJORROAD. These fields were either based on another field (example: CFCCCODE was calculated based on the TYPE attribute) or based on the segment's spatial relationship to another feature class. For example, the GNISTWP attribute was calculated based on the spatial relationship between the midline segment and the township layer.
The Street Midline schema did not provide left/right attribute fields for GNIS state, county, or township. The segments that fall on these boundaries were populated with the information that is to the south or east of the given segment.
A manual review was administered for all spatial calculations performed on the StreetMidline feature class to ensure that the "on edge" midlines received the appropriate attribution.
I. Topology Rules
PWA corrected any topological errors arising out of the implementation of the following rules:
> 1. Street midline layer must not have dangles > 2. Street midline layer must not self-intersect > 3. Street midline layer must not self-overlap > 4. Street midline layer must not overlap > 5. Street midline layer must not intersect
J. Discrepancies
Discrepancies were created whenever:
> 1. A road realignment was required to agree with the aerial photography. > 2. A road segment was missing and needed to be added to the Street Midline feature class > 3. A noteworthy issue arose (may not always have a resolution, but PWA believed that Cook County should be made aware of it)
Discrepancy points were added to the Discrepancy Tracker Website for Cook County's review and comment.
K. Street Midline Standardizations
The corrections documented by PWA in this section had been commonly found throughout the pilot area and had been reviewed via GoToMeeting with the County to determine the standard for each situation throughout the project. Additional situations/solutions that arose while completing the project were documented as the project continued.
> 1. Alleys > a. Street midline segments that are typed as Alley must be within an established > ROW polygon. > b. If a polygon does not exist, the Alley will be placed under the subtype Private > Unaddressed. > 2. Cul-de-sacs or street segment stubs - Currently four different situations have been > reviewed, each with its own standard editing process to follow. (Street names used > below are for example only.) > a. Main (through traffic) street segment is WALLEYE AVE, the cul-de-sac is given > a name of WALLEYE CT; the addresses for the residents on WALLEYE CT have been > assigned off WALLEYE AVE. > i. Solution: WALLEYE CT's subtype is changed to Midline Other ROW and > given no address range. A split remains at the intersection of WALLEYE > AVE and WALLEYE CT. Address ranges are applied to WALLEYE AVE accordingly. > b. Main (through traffic) street segment is WALLEYE AVE, the cul-de-sac is given > a name of WALLEYE CT; the residents along WALLEYE CT have been given an address > with a street name of WALLEYE CT but the addresses are all EVEN (or ODD), as if > they were addressed off WALLEYE AVE. > i. Solution: WALLEYE CT will be given an address range of Evens (or Odds) > on both the right and left sides of the street. The street segment will > be addressed to allow for increasing values on both sides of the street > (meaning the high and low address range numbers on one side of the > segment will be from a high value to a low value). Geocoding has tested > successfully in this case. > c. Main (through traffic) street segment is WALLEYE AVE, the cul-de-sac is given a > name of WALLEYE, CT the residents along WALLEYE CT have been given an address > with a street name of WALLEYE CT and ODD/EVEN addresses have been assigned. > i. Solution: Correct - No action needed. > d. Main (through traffic) street segment is WALLEYE AVE, the cul-de-sac is given a > name of WALLEYE AVE or UNKNOWN; the addresses for the residents on the cul-de-sac > have been assigned off WALLEYE AVE. > i. Solution: The cul-de-sac segment will be typed as "Midline Unnamed ROW". > The same name of the intersecting segment will be applied to the St Name > fields. > 3. Driveways/Entrances to businesses > a. Subtype of Private Unaddressed > b. If a road to a business off of an addressable road continues through to another > addressable road, the split in the main roads will be left as is. > c. If the driveway only accesses a single property, the intersecting primary > addressable road will be merged and attributes will be adjusted. > 4. For situations where roads that have sequence addresses on one side of the street 1,2,3 > 1st AVE all along the right side of the street, the following procedure will be followed: > a. The road segment will be addressed in ascending order along the one side and > descending order on the other. > 5. Bike trails (if found) that are typed as OtherRoads will be exported to a separate > feature class called Trail. > 6. Street midline segments that are given a Type of Midline Unimproved ROW will be > reviewed. If a segment is typed Midline Unimproved ROW and an address range is not > needed (since a road does not exist for the segment on aerial photography) the segment > will be removed from StreetMidline and placed into the UnimprovedROWLine feature class. > 7. If a street midline segment is found in a vacated or abandoned ROW and the aerial > photography clearly shows a built road the street midline segment will be given a type > of Private. > 8. If at a road intersection the cross streets do not meet at a given vertex and the cross > streets are separated by 5 feet or less the nodes will be corrected so that the four > street segments meet at the same given point. > 9. Frontage Roads > a. If an address has been assigned off the main road (in this example E Palatine Rd) > name the Frontage Roads, E Palatine Rd and apply the address range accordingly > (with zeros to the inside). Leave the main E Palatine road (middle segment) with > a zero address range and flag with the frontage road anomaly. > b. If a road runs parallel to a main road and the addresses are given off the main > road, apply that name and given address range to the frontage and give the road > segment the type of frontage (type of frontage dependent on the type of main road). > c. If the road segment is not parallel then do the same as above but leave the type > as Other, Private, or whatever the main road is do not change to a frontage > subtype. > 10. Cul-de-sac segments with a looped segment at the end of the arc (as shown below) > should be handled as follows: > a. The end arc (circle segment) can be deleted > b. The main road segment will be flagged with an Anomaly of "EXTEND CUL-DE-SAC SEGMENT"
L. Rural Routes
The Endeavor report (received from ETSB) was used to identify all existing rural route addresses (with associated midline names). This assisted in verifying which rural route MSAG ranges were valid. Unnecessary rural route address ranges were not be entered into the Street Midline feature class. In certain situations, new "floating segments" were added to the midlines to allow for the combination of the rural route address and street address ranges. Additional segments were added at an offset of ten feet (10') from the existing midline and typed as "E911".
If a high/low range was not used from the Cook County MSAG, it was flagged. All flagged records were sent to ETSB for further review and MSAG editing.
Before the CAD system was loaded with Street Midline data, it had been determined that Alley segments should be removed, along with StreetMidline subtypes that existed for cartographic purposes only. (23, 30, 4, 31, 5, & 6)

QUALITY ASSURANCE
PWA utilized automated tools for performing geocoding analysis and consistency checking. Additionally, a web-based, collaborative tool was deployed in order to provide the County with near real-time project updates and to allow the County to provide clarifications and corrections to any data quality assurance (DQA) issues identified by PWA. PWA technicians were responsible for flagging discrepancies throughout the pilot and final project phases, integrating any updates provided by the County staff, and verifying that the final data products satisfied the following DQA checkpoints.
> 1. The Street Midline layer will be topologically consistent. > 2. The spatial and attribute relationships between the Street Midline and Address Point > layer will satisfy all of the consistency checks imposed by PWA's in-house geocode > analyzer tools. Those checks included, but were not limited to: > a. Address ordering analysis > b. Address range gap analysis > c. Address point validation
In addition to the above DQA specifications, PWA leveraged its Collaborative Project Management Tools (CPMT) to track any and all issues that arose during data development. The Project Managers and Technical Lead provided the County with regular updates on the number, severity and resolution of these issues on a regular and timely basis.

overview.eaover: This dataset contains a polyline feature class that represents the location of the interpreted midline between the compiled edges of pavement. Unimproved rights-of-way are also included in this database. The street midlines were collected as linear features with nodes at intersections. Key attributes within this feature class are too numerous to breifly describe. Please refer to the next section, Entity_and_Attribute_Detail_Citation, to access a full listing of attributes.
